pr_review_comment_body:
Should use struct initialization format here:
```
metadata := sops.Metadata{
   UnencryptedSuffix: ....
}
```

nit: I think this makes it look as if .yaml and .yml were actually different things. I would prefer:

```
if strings.HasSuffix(path, ".yaml") || strings.HasSuffix(path, ".yml") {
 	return &yaml.Store{}
} ...
```
Instead

Should we add a writeable() back compat that will check:
```py
if hasattr(download_target, 'writeable'):
    return download_target.writeable()
return hasattr(download_target, 'write)
```
Jordon is doing the same thing for nonseekable uploads but for ``readable``

I've been playing with a one-line version of this that may be a bit more readable (that may be subjective, but the deletion of keys threw me at first in the current version):

```
return {instance: fsic2.get(instance, 0) for instance, counter in iteritems(fsic1) if fsic2.get(instance, 0) < counter}
```

I did some speed benchmarks, and it seems to depend. With a small number of keys (< 1000), your version is substantially faster. With a large number of keys, my one-liner is faster. When the two dictionaries are identical (or don't have many differences), my version seems to be faster (probably because you're starting with a full dict and then deleting everything in it one by one). The numbers we're talking about are small (it's a fast function in any case), and since it may be fairly common for the fsics to be largely the same (with legacy instance IDs sticking around but not changing), you might consider the one-liner if it doesn't feel too obtuse. Alternatively, here's a few-liner that performs similarly:

```
    fsic = {}
    for instance, counter in iteritems(fsic1):
        fsic2counter = fsic2.get(instance, 0)
        if fsic2counter < counter:
            fsic[instance] = fsic2counter
    return fsic
```

